Again: If the Foundation of God's Fore-knowledge ſtands ſure;
This deſtroys our Zeal for Good Works, for whether with, or without them, ſhall unavoidably be in Heaven or Hell; and if we happen to know that the moſt Part of Mankind ſhall be damned, this leſſens our Love to them, we believe it is the Will of God they ſhould die. Yea; tho' we ſhould not know whether they ſhall be in Heaven or Hell, only believe they ſhall land in the one or in the other, our Labour is vain, &c.
Which is your fourth Conſequence, §. 17.

Again, This Doctrine of Fore-knowledge
makes the Chriſtian Revelation contradict itſelf;
for Inſtance, The Aſſertors of it interpret that Text, He is not willing that any ſhould periſh, &c. as implying that God made no Man to be damned, quite contrary to that Text, Prov. xvi. 4. The Lord made All for himſelf, yea, even the Wicked for the Day of Evil; which is your ſixth Conſequence.
